'''Agrinierite''' ([[potassium|K]]<sub>2</sub>([[calcium|Ca]],[[strontium|Sr]])([[uranium|U]][[oxygen|O]]<sub>2</sub>)<sub>3</sub>O<sub>3</sub>(O[[hydrogen|H]])<sub>2</sub>·5H<sub>2</sub>O) is a [[mineral]] often found in the oxidation zone of uranium deposits. It is named for [[Henry Agrinier]] (1928–1971), an engineer for the [[Commissariat à l'Énergie Atomique]].
== External links == *[http://www.mindat.org/min-58.html Mindat.org - Agrinierite] *[http://www.webmineral.com/data/Agrinierite.shtml Webmineral.com - Agrinierite] *[http://www.handbookofmineralogy.com/pdfs/agrinierite.pdf Handbook of Mineralogy - Agrinierite]
[[Category:Uranium minerals]] [[Category:Orthorhombic minerals]] {{oxide-mineral-stub}}

'''Emotional Selection''' is a [[psychological]] theory of [[dream]]ing that describes dreams as modifiers and tests of [[Schema (psychology)|mental schemas]] to better meet waking [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs|human needs]]. It was introduced by Richard Coutts in 2008<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coutts|first=Richard|date=2008|title=Dreams as modifiers and tests of mental schemas: an emotional selection hypothesis|url=http://prx.sagepub.com/content/102/2/561.abstract|journal=Psychological Reports|doi=10.2466/pr0.102.2.561-574|pmid=18567225|access-date=|volume=102|pages=561–74}}</ref> and refined by him in 2010.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coutts|first=Richard|date=2010|title=A Pilot Study for the Analysis of Dream Reports Using Maslow's Need Categories: An Extension to the Emotional Selection Hypothesis|url=http://prx.sagepub.com/content/107/2/659.abstract|journal=Psychological Reports|doi=10.2466/09.PR0.107.5.659-673|pmid=21117494|access-date=|volume=107|pages=659–73}}</ref> According to emotional selection, during [[non-REM sleep]], the mind processes [[dream]]s with content intended to improve the ability of [[Schema (psychology)|mental schemas]]. For example, individuals struggling with self-perceptions of incompetence may process dreams in which they successfully navigate complex situations, those who struggle to meet belongingness needs may have dreams of entering a partner relationship, and so forth. Regardless, the theme of the non-REM dream is tentatively [[accommodation (psychology)|accommodated]] by [[Schema (psychology)|mental schemas]]. Because [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] coexist as a [[wikt:network|network]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The construction of reality|author1=Arbib, M.A |author2= Hesse, M.B. |last-author-amp=yes |publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1986|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> [[accommodation (psychology)|accommodations]] can introduce accidental, maladaptive conflicts<ref>{{Cite book|title=The equilibration of cognitive structures: the central problem of intellectual development|last=Piaget|first=J.|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1975|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and therefore are ideally tested prior to full integration. Therefore, during subsequent [[REM sleep]], a second set of [[dream]]s is executed in the form of [[scenario testing|test scenarios]]. If [[Schema (psychology)|schema]] [[accommodation (psychology)|accommodations]] performed during prior [[non-REM]] [[dream]]s alleviate anxiety, frustration, sadness, or in other ways appear [[emotions|emotionally]] adaptive during [[Rapid eye movement sleep|REM]] dream tests, they would be [[Selection (biology)|selected]] for retention. Those [[accommodation (psychology)|accommodations]] that compare negatively to existing, unchanged [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] would be abandoned or further modified and tested.

REM dreams are often described in the academic literature as having bizarre themes.<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Revonsuo, A. |author2= Salmivalli, C. |last-author-amp=yes |date=1995|title=A content analysis of bizarre elements in dreams|url=|journal=Dreaming|doi=10.1037/h0094433|pmid=|access-date= |volume=5 |pages=169–187}}</ref> According to Coutts, this description fits neatly in emotional selection. During the development of complex systems, engineers often test with rigorous, outwardly bizarre scenarios, such as intentionally crashing expensive automobiles, dropping functioning electronics onto hard surfaces, or vibrating scale models of buildings on shake tables.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Flying buttresses, entropy, and o-rings: the world of an engineer|last=Adams|first=J. L.|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1991|isbn=9780674306899|location=|pages=}}</ref> Such extreme, costly tests assure that designs meet specifications. The themes of REM dreams are often likewise extreme and bizarre, such as being chase down an alley by a monster, finding oneself naked in the presence of a crowd of people, or realizing that one's teeth or hair are falling out. When such themes are reviewed as tests of the ability of [[Schema (psychology)|mental schemas]] to cope with extreme stress, they appear rational.

According to emotional selection, pleasant  dreams, such as having sex, finding riches, or suddenly being able to fly, are tests that evaluate a person's ability to cope with success. This concept may appear to be an oxymoron. However, the challenges of coping with success are often poignantly depicted by people with self-destructive behaviors, such as substance abuse.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Cognitive therapy: the basics and beyond|last=Beck|first=Aaron|publisher=The Guilford Press|year=1995|isbn=978-1609185046|location=|pages=}}</ref> Success thrust upon those with a poor self-image can cause such people to reject the notion that they are worthy of good fortune, which is why related [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] must be modified and tested with dreams. From Coutts' 2008 paper, "People strive for independence, yet find solace in the company of others; they place a high priority on our personal safety, yet quickly jeopardize it to help [[Abraham Maslow|those]] in need; they are sexually attracted to many people, yet seek loving, [[monogamous]] relationships. [[Schema (psychology)|Schemas]] help strike the balances necessary for navigating the complex, often contradictory landscape that comprises life."<ref name="Abstracts A-D">{{cite web|last=Coutts|first=Richard|title=Richard Coutts, Abstracts A-D|url=http://www.asdreams.org/2008/abstracts/abstractsA-D.html|accessdate=August 4, 2012}}</ref>

The [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] targeted by emotional selection are those essential for meeting [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs|human needs]], such as those define by [[Abraham Maslow]] and [[Henry Murray]]. Consequently, emotional selection theory agrees with [[evolution]]ary forces by describing a role for [[dream]]s as adaptively enhancing [[Schema (psychology)|mental schemas]].

That dreams facilitate the selection of adaptive mental schemas supports the survival value description of emotional communication in general. The German philosopher [[Ferdinand Fellmann]] proposed in 2009 emotional selection as a third form of evolutionary selection besides natural and sexual selection.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fellmann|first=Ferdinand|date=2009|title=Das Paar als Quelle des Selbst. Zu den soziobiologischen Grundlagen der philosophischen Anthropologie|url=|journal=Deutsche Zeitschrift für Philosophie |volume=57 |issue=5 |pages=745–56|doi=10.1524/dzph.2009.0062|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> Loving, monogamous [[pair bond|pair-bonding]] seems to be the favored field where sexual selection is being transformed in emotional selection specific for human courtship and mating.

The concept of emotional selection fits the recent trend of evolutionary psychology which suggests that individual differences are more than the raw material upon which natural selection operates as a homogenizing force. Instead, personality and individual differences are created by “psychosocial selection”<ref>{{Cite book|title=Evolution: The Modern Synthesis|last=Huxley|first=Julian|publisher=The MIT Press|year=1942|isbn=9780262513661|location=|pages=}}</ref> in the more intense forms of pair-bonding in primate sociality. Pair-bonds are based on detecting and supporting emotional complexity in partners with whom we maintain long-term intimate intercourse.

