[[File:Charnockite, ubatuba - br.jpg|thumb|Green ubatuba, polished (size 12x10 cm)]]
'''Green ubatuba''' (Port. '''verde ubatuba''') is the commercial name of a Brazilian [[charnockite]], although it is often sold as a [[granite]]. It comes from the [[Ubatuba]] area of [[Brazil]], where it forms part of the Neoproterozoic Ribeira Belt.<ref name="Pivko">{{cite journal|last=Pivko|first=D.|year=2003|title=Natural stones in Earth's history|journal=Acta Geologica Universitatis Comenianae|volume=58|pages=73–86|url=http://212.128.130.23/eduCommons/ciencias-experimentales/rocas-industriales/contenidos/pivko.pdf|accessdate=28 May 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704180933/http://212.128.130.23/eduCommons/ciencias-experimentales/rocas-industriales/contenidos/pivko.pdf|archivedate=4 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As its name indicates, it is green in color, dark green and almost a black appearance when seen in low light. It contains large (10&nbsp;cm) [[phenocryst]]s of [[alkali feldspar]].<ref name="Vargas">{{cite web|url=http://rochasornamentais1.tripod.com/2001/Itu2/Itu2.pdf|title=Rochas ornamentais do Brasil, seu modo de ocorrencia geologica, varriedade tipologica, explotacao comercial e utilidades como materiais nobres de construcao|last=Vargas|first=T. |author2=Motoki A.  |author3=Neves J.L.P.|work=Revista de Geociências, 2-2|publisher=UFF|language=Portuguese|accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref> It is widely used in home renovations and landscaping.

