[[File:Tepey%C3%B3llotl_1.jpg#/media/File:Tepey%C3%B3llotl_1.jpg|thumb|right|Tepeyollotl, Codex Borgia.]]
[[Image:Tepeyollotl.jpg|thumb|right|Tepeyollotl in the [[Codex Telleriano-Remensis]].]] In [[Aztec mythology]], '''Tepēyōllōtl''' {{IPA-nah|tepeːˈju˕ːɬːu˕ːtɬ}} ("heart of the mountains"; also '''Tepeyollotli''') was the god of [[earthquake]]s, [[echo (phenomenon)|echoes]] and [[jaguar]]s. He is the god of the Eighth Hour of the Night, and is depicted as a jaguar leaping towards the sun. In the calendar, Tepeyollotl rules over both the third day, Calli (house), and the third trecena, 1-Mazatl (deer). He is the eighth Lord of the Night.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azteccalendar.com/god/Tepeyollotl.html|title=Tepeyollotl, the Heart of the Mountain|website=www.azteccalendar.com}}</ref>
The word is derived as a compound of the [[Nahuatl]] words ''{{Lang|nci|tepētl}}'' ("mountain"), and ''{{Lang|nci|yōllōtl}}'' ("heart" or "interior"). Tepeyollotl is usually depicted as cross-eyed holding the typical white staff with green feathers. Sometimes Tezcatlipoca wore Tepeyollotl for an animal skin or disguise to trick other gods into not knowing who he was.
